<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="223" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
Mystax whitish. Katatergal setae whitish. Anatergite with white setae. Scutellum disc with minute yellow-white setae. Mesonotal macrosetae black. Wings: Discal cell microtrichose. Legs: Femora black and yellow-brown. Metathoracic femora lacking ventral macrosetae. ♀ with abdominal segments 1-5 pruinose. ♂ terminalia as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 10–12" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 10 - 12. Astochia neavensis ♂ terminalia: 10 lateral 11 dorsal 12 ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12">Figs 10-12</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" start="Figures 10–12" startId="F6">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Figures 10-12.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Astochia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astochia neavensis" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neavensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Astochia neavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
♂ terminalia: 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">10</emphasis>
lateral 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">11</emphasis>
dorsal 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">12</emphasis>
ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
In the absence of male specimens, the species was described on females alone. 
<bibRefCitation author="Londt, JGH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Natal Museum" pageId="19" pageNumber="234" pagination="241 - 251" refId="B11" refString="Londt, JGH, 1982. Afrotropical Asilidae (Diptera) 7. The genus Astochia Becker, 1913 (Asilinae: Asilini). Annals of the Natal Museum 25: 241 - 251" title="Afrotropical Asilidae (Diptera) 7. The genus Astochia Becker, 1913 (Asilinae: Asilini)." volume="25" year="1982">Londt (1982)</bibRefCitation>
redescribed the species, providing a description and illustration of the ovipositor. Now that a single male is available, which agrees well with the general description of females, it is now possible to provide the following description of the characteristic male terminalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="223">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="223">Male terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 10–12" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 10 - 12. Astochia neavensis ♂ terminalia: 10 lateral 11 dorsal 12 ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12">Figs 10-12</figureCitation>
): Unrotated. Epandrium almost 3
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide in lateral view (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 10–12" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 10 - 12. Astochia neavensis ♂ terminalia: 10 lateral 11 dorsal 12 ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), deeply incised dorsally with left and right sides narrowly joined at base; internal surfaces each with two well defined lobes, the ventral ones being large, subtriangular and extending distally beyond the dorsal elements. Hypandrium subtriangular in both lateral (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 10–12" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 10 - 12. Astochia neavensis ♂ terminalia: 10 lateral 11 dorsal 12 ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) and ventral aspects (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 10–12" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 10 - 12. Astochia neavensis ♂ terminalia: 10 lateral 11 dorsal 12 ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Gonocoxite broad in lateral view, subtriangular and characteristically pointed distally. Gonostylus well developed, dorsally directed (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 10–12" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 10 - 12. Astochia neavensis ♂ terminalia: 10 lateral 11 dorsal 12 ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus with long terminal filaments (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 10–12" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 10 - 12. Astochia neavensis ♂ terminalia: 10 lateral 11 dorsal 12 ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346340" pageId="8" pageNumber="223" tableDoi="10.3897/AfrInvertebr.60.38432.figures10-12">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
